# GPG

## Check keys

Either view 'GPG Keychain' or using the command line:

```sh
gpg --list-keys
gpg --list-keys KEY_ID (the one in .gitconfig)
```

To get the key ID, use:

```sh
gpg --list-secret-keys --keyid-format LONG
```

And look for the part after `sec rsa4096/<KEY_ID>`

## Rotating key

### Create new key

```sh
gpg --full-generate-key
```

- Choose RSA 4096 bits for signing and encryption.
- Set expiration 2-4 years
- Use same name / email "Yann Vanhalewyn yann.vanhalewyn@gmail.com"

### Export new key

```sh
gpg --armor --export KEY_ID > my-new-key-public.asc
```

You can optionally export the private key for storage in 1Password:

```sh
gpg --armor --export-secret-keys KEY_ID > my-new-key-secret.asc
```

### Update the key in configs

- Update the `.gitconfig` with new key ID

```sh
git config --global user.signinkey [NEW_KEY_ID]
```

- Do the same for Jujutsu and other tools

### Test

- Make a test commit for verify signing works
- Check signature with `git log --show-signature`

### Upload

- Upload new key to GitHub.
